bject or array\n\n- `2 <= JSON.stringify(obj).length <= 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Given a deeply nested object or array `obj`, return the object `obj` with any `undefined` values replaced by `null`.\n\n`undefined` values are handled differently than `null` values when objects are converted to a JSON string using `JSON.stringify()`. This function helps ensure serialized data is free of unexpected errors.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: obj = {\"a\": undefined, \"b\": 3}\nOutput: {\"a\": null, \"b\": 3}\nExplanation: The value for obj.a has been changed from undefined to null\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: obj = {\"a\": undefined, \"b\": [\"a\", undefined]}\nOutput: {\"a\": null,\"b\": [\"a\", null]}\nExplanation: The values for obj.a and obj.b[1] have been changed from undefined to null\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `obj` is a valid JSON object or array\n\n- `2 <= JSON.stringify(obj).length <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/undefined-to-null/","problemName":"Undefined to Null","problemNumber":2775,"problemSlug":"undefined-to-null","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2775,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["JavaScript"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Write a function that accepts another function `fn` and converts the callback-based function into a promise-based function.\n\nThe function `fn` takes a callback as its first argument, along with any additional arguments `args` passed as separate inputs.\n\nThe `promisify` function returns a new function that should return a promise. The promise should resolve with the argument passed as the first parameter of the callback when the callback is invoked without error, and reject with the error when the callback is called with an error as the second argument.\n\nThe following is an example of a function that could be passed into `promisify`.","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"function sum(callback, a, b) {\n  if (a < 0 || b < 0) {\n    const err = Error('a and b must be positive');\n    callback(undefined, err);\n  } else {\n    callback(a + b);\n  }\n}","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"This is the equivalent code based on promises:","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"async function sum(a, b) {\n  if (a < 0 || b < 0) {\n    throw Error('a and b must be positive');\n  } else {\n    return a + b;\n  }\n}","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: \nfn = (callback, a, b, c) => {\n    callback(a * b * c);\n}\nargs = [1, 2, 3]\nOutput: {\"resolved\": 6}\nExplanation: \nconst asyncFunc = promisify(fn);\nasyncFunc(1, 2, 3).then(console.log); // 6\n\nfn is called with a callback as the first argument and args as the rest. The promise based version of fn resolves a value of 6 when called with (1, 2, 3).","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":7,"text":"Input: \nfn = (callback, a, b, c) => {\n    callback(a * b * c, \"Promise Rejected\");\n}\nargs = [4, 5, 6]\nOutput: {\"rejected\": \"Promise Rejected\"}\nExplanation: \nconst asyncFunc = promisify(fn);\nasyncFunc(4, 5, 6).catch(console.log); // \"Promise Rejected\"\n\nfn is called with a callback as the first argument and args as the rest. As the second argument, the callback accepts an error message, so when fn is called, the promise is rejected with a error message provided in the callback. Note that it did not matter what was passed as the first argument into the callback.","type":"code"},{"sequence":8,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= args.length <= 100`\n\n- `0 <= args[i] <= 10⁴`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Write a function that accepts another function `fn` and converts the callback-based function into a promise-based function.\n\nThe function `fn` takes a callback as its first argument, along with any additional arguments `args` passed as separate inputs.\n\nThe `promisify` function returns a new function that should return a promise. The promise should resolve with the argument passed as the first parameter of the callback when the callback is invoked without error, and reject with the error when the callback is called with an error as the second argument.\n\nThe following is an example of a function that could be passed into `promisify`.\n\nfunction sum(callback, a, b) {\n  if (a < 0 || b < 0) {\n    const err = Error('a and b must be positive');\n    callback(undefined, err);\n  } else {\n    callback(a + b);\n  }\n}\n\nThis is the equivalent code based on promises:\n\nasync function sum(a, b) {\n  if (a < 0 || b < 0) {\n    throw Error('a and b must be positive');\n  } else {\n    return a + b;\n  }\n}\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: \nfn = (callback, a, b, c) => {\n    callback(a * b * c);\n}\nargs = [1, 2, 3]\nOutput: {\"resolved\": 6}\nExplanation: \nconst asyncFunc = promisify(fn);\nasyncFunc(1, 2, 3).then(console.log); // 6\n\nfn is called with a callback as the first argument and args as the rest. The promise based version of fn resolves a value of 6 when called with (1, 2, 3).\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: \nfn = (callback, a, b, c) => {\n    callback(a * b * c, \"Promise Rejected\");\n}\nargs = [4, 5, 6]\nOutput: {\"rejected\": \"Promise Rejected\"}\nExplanation: \nconst asyncFunc = promisify(fn);\nasyncFunc(4, 5, 6).catch(console.log); // \"Promise Rejected\"\n\nfn is called with a callback as the first argument and args as the rest. As the second argument, the callback accepts an error message, so when fn is called, the promise is rejected with a error message provided in the callback. Note that it did not matter what was passed as the first argument into the callback.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= args.length <= 100`\n\n- `0 <= args[i] <= 10⁴`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/convert-callback-based-function-to-promise-based-