: 2 + 6 + 1 + 9 - 5 = 13.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [2,4,6,8], x = 3\nOutput: 20\nExplanation: All the integers in the array have the same parities, so we can visit all of them without losing any score.\nThe total score is: 2 + 4 + 6 + 8 = 20.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= nums.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i], x <= 10⁶`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/visit-array-positions-to-maximize-score/","problemName":"Visit Array Positions to Maximize Score","problemNumber":2786,"problemSlug":"visit-array-positions-to-maximize-score","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2786,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Dynamic Programming"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given two **positive** integers `n` and `x`.\n\nReturn *the number of ways *`n`* can be expressed as the sum of the *`x^(th)`* power of **unique** positive integers, in other words, the number of sets of unique integers *`[n1, n2, ..., nk]`* where *`n = n1^(x) + n2^(x) + ... + nk^(x)`*.*\n\nSince the result can be very large, return it modulo `10⁹ + 7`.\n\nFor example, if `n = 160` and `x = 3`, one way to express `n` is `n = 2³ + 3³ + 5³`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: n = 10, x = 2\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We can express n as the following: n = 32 + 12 = 10.\nIt can be shown that it is the only way to express 10 as the sum of the 2nd power of unique integers.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: n = 4, x = 1\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: We can express n in the following ways:\n- n = 41 = 4.\n- n = 31 + 11 = 4.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= n <= 300`\n\n- `1 <= x <= 5`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Dynamic Programming"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given two **positive** integers `n` and `x`.\n\nReturn *the number of ways *`n`* can be expressed as the sum of the *`x^(th)`* power of **unique** positive integers, in other words, the number of sets of unique integers *`[n1, n2, ..., nk]`* where *`n = n1^(x) + n2^(x) + ... + nk^(x)`*.*\n\nSince the result can be very large, return it modulo `10⁹ + 7`.\n\nFor example, if `n = 160` and `x = 3`, one way to express `n` is `n = 2³ + 3³ + 5³`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: n = 10, x = 2\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We can express n as the following: n = 32 + 12 = 10.\nIt can be shown that it is the only way to express 10 as the sum of the 2nd power of unique integers.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: n = 4, x = 1\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: We can express n in the following ways:\n- n = 41 = 4.\n- n = 31 + 11 = 4.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= n <= 300`\n\n- `1 <= x <= 5`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/ways-to-express-an-integer-as-sum-of-powers/","problemName":"Ways to Express an Integer as Sum of Powers","problemNumber":2787,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given two **positive** integers `n` and `x`.\n\nReturn *the number of ways *`n`* can be expressed as the sum of the *`x^(th)`* power of **unique** positive integers, in other words, the number of sets of unique integers *`[n1, n2, ..., nk]`* where *`n = n1^(x) + n2^(x) + ... + nk^(x)`*.*\n\nSince the result can be very large, return it modulo `10⁹ + 7`.\n\nFor example, if `n = 160` and `x = 3`, one way to express `n` is `n = 2³ + 3³ + 5³`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: n = 10, x = 2\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: We can express n as the following: n = 32 + 12 = 10.\nIt can be shown that it is the only way to express 10 as the sum of the 2nd power of unique integers.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: n = 4, x = 1\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: We can express n in